>
  <p>Most people go into their first therapy session with some combination of anxiety, hope, and no clear sense of what to do or say. That's completely normal. But a small amount of preparation makes the first session significantly more productive — and gives you a head start on the work.</p>
  <p>Here's what to think about, write down, and expect before you start.</p>
  <h2>1. Get Clear on Why You're Going (Even If It's Vague)</h2>
  <p>You don't need a precise articulation of your problem. But having some sense of what prompted you to reach out helps the first session get started productively.</p>
  <p>Ask yourself:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>What's been making life feel harder lately?</li>
    <li>What's the main thing I'd like to be different?</li>
    <li>What made me decide to start therapy now, rather than six months ago or six months from now?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Even rough answers — "I've been feeling really anxious and I'm not sure why" or "my relationship is suffering and I don't know how to fix it" — give your therapist a useful starting point.</p>
  <p>Write these down. Having notes in front of you in a first session can help when nerves make it hard to remember what you wanted to say.</p>
  <h2>2. Know Your Goals (Even Loosely)</h2>
  <p>What would "better" look like for you? This doesn't need to be specific — in fact, therapy often clarifies goals over time. But even a general direction helps:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>"I want to feel less anxious day-to-day"</li>
    <li>"I want to understand why I keep ending up in the same kinds of relationships"</li>
    <li>"I want to be able to function better at work"</li>
    <li>"I want to stop drinking as a coping mechanism"</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Goals don't have to be correct — they can change as the work evolves. But having a direction gives therapy early momentum.</p>
  <h2>3. Think About Your History with Mental Health (If Any)</h2>
  <p>If you've been in therapy before, reflect on what worked and what didn't. Have you taken or currently take any psychiatric medication? Have you received any mental health diagnoses?</p>
  <p>This isn't required information — you share what you're comfortable sharing — but it helps your therapist start from where you are rather than starting from scratch. Previous therapy experiences, both positive and negative, are particularly useful context.</p>
  <h2>4. Consider What You're Not Ready to Talk About</h2>
  <p>You don't have to share everything immediately. If there are areas you're not ready to go into — specific past experiences, current situations you find too raw — it's okay to acknowledge this to your therapist: "There's something I'm not ready to talk about yet, but I want you to know it exists."</p>
  <p>Good therapists work with your readiness, not against it. Knowing your own limits going in helps you manage the pacing.</p>
  <h2>5. Set Up Your Space for Online Therapy</h2>
  <p>If you're doing therapy online:</p>
  <p><strong>Privacy first.</strong> Choose a space where you can speak freely without being overheard — your own room, your car, a private space. If you share your home, let housemates or family know you'll be unavailable for the session time.</p>
  <p><strong>Headphones.</strong> Using headphones or earbuds improves audio quality and reduces the risk of being overheard.</p>
  <p><strong>Stable connection.</strong> Test your internet connection beforehand. Close unnecessary applications that might slow it down. Have a phone number as backup in case video fails.</p>
  <p><strong>Camera level.</strong> Position your camera at roughly eye level — it makes the session feel more like a real conversation.</p>
  <p><strong>Water nearby.</strong> Sessions can involve emotional content. Having water available is simply practical.</p>
  <p><strong>Buffer time.</strong> Leave at least 15–30 minutes after your session before your next obligation. The emotional residue from therapy can linger briefly, and having rushed transitions makes this harder to manage.</p>
  <h2>6. Think About Practicalities</h2>
  <p><strong>Frequency and timing.</strong> Most therapy starts weekly. Think about what timing genuinely works for your schedule — not just theoretically, but practically. Cancellations are disruptive to progress, so choosing a slot you can actually protect matters.</p>
  <p><strong>Payment.</strong> Know how you're paying and whether your insurance is involved, before the session, so this doesn't take up session time.</p>
  <p><strong>What to do if you're overwhelmed.</strong> It's normal for sessions to bring up strong feelings. Think in advance about what you'll do if you feel significantly activated during or after a session — who you might contact, what would help you ground.</p>
  <h2>7. Manage Your Expectations</h2>
  <p><strong>First sessions are usually more assessment-like than therapeutic.</strong> Your therapist is gathering information in the first session — asking questions to understand your situation. The deeper therapeutic work typically starts in sessions 2–4.</p>
  <p><strong>You might feel some discomfort.</strong> Talking about difficult things can be uncomfortable. This doesn't mean therapy isn't working. A session that's difficult is often doing something.</p>
  <p><strong>You won't know if it's the right fit immediately.</strong> Give the therapeutic relationship 3–4 sessions before evaluating whether it's working. First sessions are inherently more awkward than later ones.</p>
  <p><strong>You can switch.</strong> If you find, after genuine effort, that this therapist isn't right for you, switching is appropriate and normal. <a href="/articles/how-to-know-if-therapist-is-right">How to know if a therapist is right for you →</a></p>
  <h2>8. Questions to Ask Your Therapist in the First Session</h2>
  <p>You're evaluating your therapist as much as they're assessing you. It's appropriate to ask:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>"What's your experience working with [your specific concern]?"</li>
    <li>"What approach do you typically use?"</li>
    <li>"What might a course of therapy with you look like?"</li>
    <li>"What do you expect from clients between sessions?"</li>
  </ul>
  <p>These questions signal that you're an active participant in your own care — which is exactly the kind of client who gets the most out of therapy.</p>
  <h2>A Simple Pre-Session Checklist</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>[ ] Written down the main reason you're starting therapy</li>
    <li>[ ] Thought about what "better" would look like</li>
    <li>[ ] Noted any previous therapy or medication history</li>
    <li>[ ] Set up a private, comfortable space for the session</li>
    <li>[ ] Tested your internet connection (if online)</li>
    <li>[ ] Scheduled buffer time after the session</li>
    <li>[ ] Confirmed payment method</li>
  </ul>
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <p><strong>Should I write down everything I want to say?</strong></p>
  <p>A brief note of key points is useful — not a script. You don't need to deliver a prepared speech, and a list that's too detailed can make the session feel formal. Main concerns + what you hope for = sufficient.</p>
  <p><strong>What should I wear?</strong></p>
  <p>Whatever you're comfortable in. There's no dress code for therapy. Comfort is the goal.</p>
  <p><strong>What if I freeze up and can't think of anything to say?</strong></p>
  <p>Tell your therapist exactly that: "I had a lot I wanted to say but I'm drawing a blank right now." This is a completely valid opening. A good therapist will help you find your way in.</p>
  <p><strong>Can I bring notes to my session?</strong></p>
  <p>Yes, absolutely. Having notes in front of you — whether on paper or on your phone — is completely fine and often helps.</p>
